title: Ocean Grove Nature Reserve
description: Originally known as Cuthbertson's Paddock, this reserve covers 143 hectares and represents one of the last remaining stands of native woodland on the Bellarine Peninsula.

items.title: Caladenia tentaculata
items.content_text: 3 images with a focus on the clubbed-sepals and non-clubbed petals, a helpful diagnostic feature of this species.

items.title: Thelymitra peniculata
items.content_text: Location approximate. 2 pics, 2nd one showing the post-anther lobe from above.

items.title: Thelymitra nuda
items.content_text: Approximate location. 2 pics, 2nd one front-on image of the flower.

items.title: Wurmbea latifolia subsp. vanessae
items.content_text: An unexpected find at the Reserve. Uncommon species; also of note is the late flowering time. Often flowering 'nancies' are one of the first signs of spring flowering from July/August. 2 pics with images of the same plant taken one day apart

items.title: Thelymitra pauciflora s.s.
items.content_text: Unusual creamy white coloured Thelymitra Pauciflora. Was seen in the company of the more usual coloured blueish-mauve T. pauciflora and also T. rubra. (2 pics.)

items.title: Caladenia pusilla
items.content_text: 2 images.

items.title: Fomitopsis spp.
items.content_text: 3 images. Possibly Fomitopsis lilacinogilva ? Growing on dead trunk of Acacia pycnantha (Golden Wattle).

items.title: Pterostylis nana
items.content_text: Dwarf Greenhood orchid. 2 images, one showing rosette leaves.

items.title: Pterostylis concinna
items.content_text: 2 photos, one showing basal rosettes of several non-flowering plants. This is a common winter-flowering orchid in my local patch.

items.title: Corybas incurvus
items.content_text: 4 images of Slaty Helmet-orchids with flowers in various stages of development. Newly emerging flowers appeared in mid-July. 2 weeks later in early August the flowers were fully formed.

items.title: Corybas diemenicus s.l.
items.content_text: Three images.

items.title: Carposina telesia
items.content_text: 2nd image shows view from top.

items.title: Euproctis melanosoma
items.content_text: The ID created a challenge.  Males of this species, as featured in MOV 2 shows a white tuft end to the abdomen.  This one has an orange colour tuft as well as a black upper body and stripes on the underside of the body.  May eventually be found to be a different species.  It got knocked off the sheet by a larger insect and played dead long enough to get a photo of the underside.  Two additional images included to show the features.

items.title: Gauna aegusalis
items.content_text: Typical resting position.

items.title: Mossega indecisa
items.content_text: Thanks to Ken Harris for ID.  This is a fairly large insect - image of forewing and one of open resting pose included.

items.title: Proteuxoa sanguinipuncta
items.content_text: Another difference from P. rubripunta is the tawny colour thorax on the P. sanguinipuncta.

items.title: Proteuxoa rubripuncta
items.content_text: Note that the spot, on the forewing, is red surrounded by black where as the P. sanguinipuncta has a black spot surrounded by red in similar location.

items.title: Glyphipterix meteora, Lobelia pratioides
items.content_text: A single Glyphipterix meteora moth. Other Glyphipterix meteora moths had been observed on Burchardia umbellata (Milkmaids) the previous day. Interesting to see a similar photo by Russell Best (below) in this Lobelia species list with the same moths, plus a beetle. As mentioned by Russell Best the moth appears to be feeding from below.

items.title: Scopula rubraria
items.content_text: Single moth flowing low and stopping constantly in the long grasses. Lighter coloured form to others on this page. I note Cathy's comments about the variability in colour of this species.

items.title: Burchardia umbellata, Glyphipterix meteora
items.content_text: Glyphipterix meteora moths enjoying the pollen on Burchardia umbellata (Milkmaids). Moth ID provided by Marilyn Hewish.
